# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: payment-card-processing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] A **card security code** (**CSC**; also known as **CVC**, **CVV**, or several other names) is a series of numbers that, in addition to the bank card number, is printed (but not embossed) on a credit or debit card.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The CSC is used as a security feature for card-not-present transactions, where a personal identification number (PIN) cannot be manually entered by the cardholder (as they would during point-of-sale or card present transactions).
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] It was instituted to reduce the incidence of credit card fraud.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Unlike the card number, the CSC is deliberately not embossed, so that it is not read when using a mechanical credit card imprinter which will only pick up embossed numbers.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] These codes are in slightly different places for different card issuers.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The CSC for Visa, Mastercard, and Discover credit cards is a three-digit number on the back of the card, to the right of the signature box.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The CSC for American Express is a four-digit code on the front of the card above the account number.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] See the figures to the right for examples.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] CSC was originally developed in the UK as an eleven-character alphanumeric code by Equifax employee Michael Stone in 1995.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] After testing with the Littlewoods Home Shopping group and NatWest bank, the concept was adopted by the UK Association for Payment Clearing Services (APACS) and streamlined to the three-digit code known today.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Mastercard started issuing CVC2 numbers in 1997 and Visa in the United States issued them by 2001.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] American Express started to use the CSC in 1999, in response to growing Internet transactions and card member complaints of spending interruptions when the security of a card has been brought into question.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The card security code is typically the last three or four digits printed, not embossed like the card number, on the signature strip on the back of the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] On American Express cards, however, the card security code is the four digits printed (not embossed) on the front towards the right.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The card security code is not encoded on the magnetic stripe but is printed flat.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The CSC for each card (form 1 and 2) is generated by the card issuer when the card is issued.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] It is calculated by encrypting the bank card number and expiration date (two fields printed on the card) with encryption keys known only to the card issuer, and decimalising the result (in a similar manner to a hash function).
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] As a security measure, merchants who require the CVV2 for card-not-present transactions are required by the card issuer not to store the CVV2 once the individual transaction is authorized.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] This way, if a database of transactions is compromised, the CVV2 is not present and the stolen card numbers are less useful.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Virtual terminals and payment gateways do not store the CVV2 code; therefore, employees and customer service representatives with access to these web-based payment interfaces, who otherwise have access to complete card numbers, expiration dates, and other information, still lack the CVV2 code.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) also prohibits the storage of CSC (and other sensitive authorisation data) post transaction authorisation.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] This applies globally to anyone who stores, processes or transmits cardholder data.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Since the CSC is not contained on the magnetic stripe of the card, it is not typically included in the transaction when the card is used face to face at a merchant.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] However, some merchants in North America, such as Sears and Staples, require the code.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] For American Express cards, this has been an invariable practice (for card-not-present transactions) in European Union (EU) countries like Ireland and the United Kingdom since the start of 2005.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] This provides a level of protection to the bank/cardholder, in that a fraudulent merchant or employee cannot simply capture the magnetic stripe details of a card and use them later for card-not-present transactions over the phone, mail order or Internet.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] To do this, a merchant or its employee would also have to note the CVV2 visually and record it, which is more likely to arouse the cardholder's suspicion.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Supplying the CSC code in a transaction is intended to verify that the customer has the card in their possession.
[src:payment-card-processing/card-security-code] Knowledge of the code proves that the customer has seen the card, or has seen a record made by somebody who saw the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV cards are smart cards, also called chip cards, integrated circuit cards (ICC), or IC cards, which store their data on integrated circuit chips, in addition to magnetic stripes for backward compatibility.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] These include cards that must be physically inserted or "dipped" into a reader, as well as contactless cards that can be read over a short distance using near-field communication technology.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Payment cards which comply with the EMV standard are often called **chip and PIN** or **chip and signature** cards, depending on the authentication methods employed by the card issuer, such as a personal identification number (PIN) or electronic signature.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Standards exist, based on ISO/IEC 7816, for contact cards, and based on ISO/IEC 14443 for contactless cards (Mastercard Contactless, Visa PayWave, American Express ExpressPay).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Until the introduction of chip & PIN, all face-to-face credit or debit card transactions involved the use of a magnetic stripe or mechanical imprint to read and record account data, and a signature for purposes of identity verification.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The customer hands their card to the cashier at the point of sale who then passes the card through a magnetic reader or makes an imprint from the raised text of the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In the former case, the system verifies account details and prints a slip for the customer to sign.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In the case of a mechanical imprint, the transaction details are filled in, a list of stolen numbers is consulted, and the customer signs the imprinted slip.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] For larger transactions, authorization might be obtained by the merchant telephoning a hotline and obtaining a code which is written onto the slip.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In both cases the cashier must verify that the customer's signature matches that on the back of the card to authenticate the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Using the signature on the card as a verification method has a number of security flaws, the most obvious being the relative ease with which cards may go missing before their legitimate owners can sign them.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Another involves the erasure and replacement of legitimate signature, and yet another involves the forgery of the correct signature.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The invention of the silicon integrated circuit chip in 1959 led to the idea of incorporating it onto a plastic smart card in the late 1960s by two German engineers, Helmut Gröttrup and Jürgen Dethloff.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The earliest smart cards were introduced as calling cards in the 1970s, before later being adapted for use as payment cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Smart cards have since used MOS integrated circuit chips, along with MOS memory technologies such as flash memory and EEPROM (electrically erasable programmable read-only memory).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The first standard for smart payment cards was the Carte Bancaire B0M4 from Bull-CP8 deployed in France in 1986, followed by the B4B0' (compatible with the M4) deployed in 1989.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV was designed to allow cards and terminals to be backwardly compatible with these standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] France has since migrated all its card and terminal infrastructure to EMV.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV stands for Europay, Mastercard, and Visa, the three companies that created the standard.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The standard is now managed by EMVCo, a consortium with control split equally among Visa, Mastercard, JCB, American Express, China UnionPay, and Discover.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMVCo accepts public comment on its draft standards and processes, but also allows other organizations to become "Associates" and "Subscribers" for deeper collaboration.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] JCB joined the consortium in February 2009, China UnionPay in May 2013, and Discover in September 2013.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The top vendors of EMV cards and chips are: ABnote (American Bank Corp), CPI Card Group, IDEMIA (from the merger of Oberthur Technologies and Safran Identity & Security (Morpho) in 2017), Gemalto (acquired by the Thales Group in 2019) Giesecke & Devrient and Versatile Card Technology.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] There are two major benefits to moving to smart-card-based card payment systems: improved security (with associated fraud reduction), and the possibility for finer control of "offline" card transaction approvals.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] One of the original goals of EMV was to provide for multiple applications on a card: for a credit and debit card application or an e-purse.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Beginning in 2013, new-issue debit cards in the US contain two applications: a card association (Visa, Mastercard etc.) application, and a common debit application.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV chip card transactions improve security against fraud compared to magnetic stripe card transactions that rely on the cardholder's signature and visual inspection of the card to check for features such as hologram.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The use of a PIN and cryptographic algorithms such as Triple DES, RSA and SHA provide authentication of the card to the processing terminal and the card issuer's host system.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The processing time is comparable to online transactions, in which communications delay accounts for the majority of the time, while cryptographic operations at the terminal take comparatively little time.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The supposed increased protection from fraud has allowed banks and card issuers to establish a "liability shift", such that merchants are liable (as of 1 January 2005 in the EU region and 1 October 2015 in the US) for any fraud that results from transactions on systems that are not EMV-capable.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The majority of implementations of EMV cards and terminals confirm the identity of the cardholder by requiring the entry of a personal identification number (PIN) rather than signing a paper receipt.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Whether or not PIN authentication takes place depends upon the capabilities of the terminal and programming of the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] When payment cards were first introduced, merchants used mechanical rather than magnetic portable card imprinters that required carbon paper to make an imprint.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] They did not communicate electronically with the card issuer, and the card never left the customer's sight.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The merchant had to verify transactions over a certain amount by telephoning the card issuer.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] During the 1970s in the United States, many merchants subscribed to a regularly-updated list of stolen or otherwise invalid credit card numbers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This list was commonly printed in booklet form on newsprint, in numerical order, much like a slender phone book, yet without any data aside from the list of invalid numbers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Checkout cashiers were expected to thumb through this booklet each and every time a credit card was presented for payment of any amount, prior to approving the transaction, which incurred a short delay.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Later, terminal equipment at the merchant electronically contacted the card issuer, using information from the magnetic stripe to verify the card and authorize the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This was much faster, but required the transaction to occur in a fixed location.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Consequently, if the transaction did not take place near a terminal (in a restaurant, for example) the clerk or waiter had to take the card away from the customer and to the card machine.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] It was possible for a dishonest employee to easily swipe the card surreptitiously through a machine that recorded the information on the card and magnetic stripe.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Since the introduction of chip and PIN, cloning of the chip is not feasible; only the magnetic stripe can be copied, and a copied card cannot be used by itself at a terminal requiring a PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The introduction of chip and PIN coincided with wireless data transmission technology becoming inexpensive and widespread.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In addition to mobile-phone-based magnetic readers, merchant personnel can now bring wireless PIN pads to the customer, so the card is never out of the cardholder's sight.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Thus, both chip and PIN and wireless technologies can be used to reduce the risks of unauthorized swiping and card cloning.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Chip and PIN is one of the two verification methods that EMV enabled cards can employ.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Rather than physically signing a receipt for identification purposes, the user enters a personal identification number (PIN), typically of four to six digits in length.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This number must correspond to the information stored on the chip or PIN at Host.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Chip and PIN technology makes it much harder for fraudsters to use a found card, inasmuch as if someone steals a card, they are unable to make fraudulent purchases unless they know the PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Chip and signature, on the other hand, differentiates itself from chip and PIN by verifying a consumer's identity with a signature.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] As of 2015, chip and PIN cards are common in most European countries (e.g., the UK, Ireland, France, Portugal, Finland and the Netherlands) as well as in Pakistan, Iran, Brazil, Colombia, Venezuela, India, Sri Lanka, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Chip and signature cards are more common in the US, Mexico, parts of South America (such as Argentina and Peru) and some Asian countries (such as Taiwan, Hong Kong, Thailand, South Korea, Singapore, and Indonesia).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] While EMV technology has helped reduce crime at the point of sale, fraudulent transactions have shifted to more vulnerable telephone, Internet, and mail order transactions—known in the industry as card-not-present or CNP transactions.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] CNP transactions made up at least 50% of all credit card fraud.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] ISO/IEC 7816-3 defines the transmission protocol between chip cards and readers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Using this protocol, data is exchanged in *application protocol data units* (APDUs).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This comprises sending a command to a card, the card processing it, and sending a response.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Commands followed by "7816-4" are defined in ISO/IEC 7816-4 and are interindustry commands used for many chip card applications such as GSM SIM cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] ISO/IEC 7816 defines a process for application selection.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The intent of application selection was to let cards contain completely different applications—for example GSM and EMV.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] However, EMV developers implemented application selection as a way of identifying the type of product, so that all product issuers (Visa, Mastercard, etc.) must have their own application.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The way application selection is prescribed in EMV is a frequent source of interoperability problems between cards and terminals.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Book 1 of the EMV standard devotes 15 pages to describing the application selection process.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] An *application identifier* (AID) is used to address an application in the card or Host Card Emulation (HCE) if delivered without a card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] An AID consists of a *registered application provider identifier* (RID) of five bytes, which is issued by the ISO/IEC 7816-5 registration authority.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This is followed by a *proprietary application identifier extension* (PIX), which enables the application provider to differentiate among the different applications offered.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The AID is printed on all EMV cardholder receipts.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Card issuers can alter the application name from the name of the card network.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal sends the *get processing options* command to the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] When issuing this command, the terminal supplies the card with any data elements requested by the card in the *processing options data objects list* (PDOL).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The PDOL (a list of tags and lengths of data elements) is optionally provided by the card to the terminal during application selection.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The card responds with the *application interchange profile* (AIP), a list of functions to perform in processing the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The card also provides the *application file locator* (AFL), a list of files and records that the terminal needs to read from the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The AFL contains the files that contain EMV data.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] These all must be read using the read record command.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV does not specify which files data is stored in, so all the files must be read.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Data in these files is stored in BER TLV format.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV defines tag values for all data used in card processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The purpose of the *processing restrictions* is to see if the card should be used.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Three data elements read in the previous step are checked: Application version number, Application usage control (this shows whether the card is only for domestic use, etc.), Application effective/expiration dates checking.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] If any of these checks fails, the card is not necessarily declined.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal sets the appropriate bit in the terminal verification results (TVR), the components of which form the basis of an accept/decline decision later in the transaction flow.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This feature lets, for example, card issuers permit cardholders to keep using expired cards after their expiry date, but for all transactions with an expired card to be performed on-line.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Offline data authentication is a cryptographic check to validate the card using public-key cryptography.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] To verify the authenticity of payment cards, EMV certificates are used.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The EMV Certificate Authority issues digital certificates to payment card issuers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] When requested, the payment card chip provides the card issuer's public key certificate and Signed Static Application Data (SSAD) to the terminal.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal retrieves the CA's public key from local storage and uses it to confirm trust for the CA and, if trusted, to verify the card issuer's public key was signed by the CA.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] If the card issuer's public key is valid, the terminal uses the card issuer's public key to verify the card's SSAD was signed by the card issuer.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Cardholder verification is used to evaluate whether the person presenting the card is the legitimate cardholder.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] There are many cardholder verification methods (CVMs) supported in EMV.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal uses a CVM list read from the card to determine the type of verification to perform.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The CVM list establishes a priority of CVMs to use relative to the capabilities of the terminal.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Different terminals support different CVMs.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] POS terminals vary in their CVM support depending on type and country.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] For offline enciphered PIN methods, the terminal encrypts the cleartext PIN block with the card's public key before sending it to the card with the Verify command.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] For the online PIN method, the cleartext PIN block is encrypted by the terminal using its point-to-point encryption key before sending it to the acquirer processor in the authorization request message.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] All offline methods are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In 2017, EMVCo added support for biometric verification methods in version 4.3 of the EMV specifications.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Terminal risk management is only performed in devices where there is a decision to be made whether a transaction should be authorised on-line or offline.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] If transactions are always carried out on-line (e.g., ATMs) or always off-line, this step can be skipped.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Terminal risk management checks the transaction amount against an offline ceiling limit (above which transactions should be processed on-line).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] It is also possible to have a 1 in an online counter, and a check against a hot card list (which is only necessary for off-line transactions).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] If the result of any of these tests is positive, the terminal sets the appropriate bit in the terminal verification results (TVR).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The results of previous processing steps are used to determine whether a transaction should be approved offline, sent online for authorization, or declined offline.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This is done using a combination of data objects known as *terminal action codes* (TACs) held in the terminal and *issuer action codes* (IACs) read from the card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The TAC is logically OR'd with the IAC, to give the transaction acquirer a level of control over the transaction outcome.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Both types of action code take the values Denial, Online, and Default.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Each action code contains a series of bits which correspond to the bits in the Terminal verification results (TVR), and are used in the terminal's decision whether to accept, decline or go on-line for a payment transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The TAC is set by the card acquirer; in practice card schemes advise the TAC settings that should be used for a particular terminal type depending on its capabilities.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The IAC is set by the card issuer; some card issuers may decide that expired cards should be rejected, by setting the appropriate bit in the Denial IAC.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Other issuers may want the transaction to proceed on-line so that they can in some cases allow these transactions to be carried out.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] When an online-only device performs IAC-Online and TAC-Online processing the only relevant TVR bit is "Transaction value exceeds the floor limit".
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Because the floor limit is set to zero, the transaction should always go online and all other values in TAC-Online or IAC-Online are irrelevant.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Online-only devices do not need to perform IAC-default processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] An online-only device such as an ATM always attempts to go on-line with the authorization request, unless declined off-line due to IAC-Denial settings.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] During IAC-Denial and TAC-Denial processing, for an online only device, the only relevant Terminal verification results bit is "Service not allowed".
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] One of the data objects read from the card in the Read application data stage is CDOL1 (Card Data object List).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This object is a list of tags that the card wants to be sent to it to make a decision on whether to approve or decline a transaction (including transaction amount, but many other data objects too).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal sends this data and requests a cryptogram using the generate application cryptogram command.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This step gives the card the opportunity to accept the terminal's action analysis or to decline a transaction or force a transaction on-line.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The card cannot return a TC when an ARQC has been asked for, but can return an ARQC when a TC has been asked for.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Transactions go online when an ARQC has been requested.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The ARQC is sent in the authorisation message.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Its format depends on the card application.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV does not specify the contents of the ARQC.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The ARQC created by the card application is a digital signature of the transaction details, which the card issuer can check in real time.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This provides a strong cryptographic check that the card is genuine.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The issuer responds to an authorization request with a response code (accepting or declining the transaction), an authorisation response cryptogram (ARPC) and optionally an issuer script (a string of commands to be sent to the card).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] ARPC processing is not performed in contact transactions processed with Visa Quick Chip for EMV and Mastercard M/Chip Fast, and in contactless transactions across schemes because the card is removed from the reader after the ARQC has been generated.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] CDOL2 (Card data object list) contains a list of tags that the card wanted to be sent after online transaction authorisation (response code, ARPC, etc.).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Even if for any reason the terminal could not go online (e.g., communication failure), the terminal should send this data to the card again using the generate authorisation cryptogram command.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This lets the card know the issuer's response.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The card application may then reset offline usage limits.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] If a card issuer wants to update a card post issuance it can send commands to the card using issuer script processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Issuer scripts are meaningless to the terminal and can be encrypted between the card and the issuer to provide additional security.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Issuer script can be used to block cards, or change card parameters.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Issuer script processing is not available in contact transactions processed with Visa Quick Chip for EMV and Mastercard M/Chip Fast, and for contactless transactions across schemes.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The EMV standard is defined and managed by the privately owned corporation EMVCo LLC.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The current members of EMVCo are American Express, Discover Financial, JCB International, Mastercard, China UnionPay, and Visa Inc.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Each of these organizations owns an equal share of EMVCo and has representatives in the EMVCo organization and EMVCo working groups.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The first EMV standard came into view in 1995 as EMV 2.0.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This was upgraded to EMV 3.0 in 1996 (sometimes referred to as EMV '96) with later amendments to EMV 3.1.1 in 1998.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This was further amended to version 4.0 in December 2000 (sometimes referred to as EMV 2000).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Version 4.0 became effective in June 2004.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Version 4.1 became effective in June 2007.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Version 4.2 is in effect since June 2008.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Version 4.3 is in effect since November 2011.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Recognition of compliance with the EMV standard (i.e., device certification) is issued by EMVCo following submission of results of testing performed by an accredited testing house.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] EMV Compliance testing has two levels: EMV Level 1, which covers physical, electrical and transport level interfaces, and EMV Level 2, which covers payment application selection and credit financial transaction processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In addition to the track-two data on the magnetic stripe, EMV cards generally have identical data encoded on the chip, which is read as part of the normal EMV transaction process.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This attack is possible only where (a) the offline PIN is presented in plaintext by the PIN entry device to the card, where (b) magstripe fallback is permitted by the card issuer and (c) where geographic and behavioural checking may not be carried out by the card issuer.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] APACS, representing the UK payment industry, claimed that changes specified to the protocol (where card verification values differ between the magnetic stripe and the chip – the iCVV) rendered this attack ineffective and that such measures would be in place from January 2008.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Tests on cards in February 2008 indicated this may have been delayed.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Conversation capturing is a form of attack which was reported to have taken place against Shell terminals in May 2006, when they were forced to disable all EMV authentication in their petrol stations after more than £1 million was stolen from customers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In October 2008, it was reported that hundreds of EMV card readers intended for use in Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, Denmark, and Belgium had been tampered with in China during or shortly after manufacture.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] For nine months, details and PINs of credit and debit cards were sent over mobile phone networks to criminals in Lahore, Pakistan.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] United States National Counterintelligence Executive Joel Brenner said, "Previously only a nation state's intelligence agency would have been capable of pulling off this type of operation.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] It's scary." Stolen data was typically used a couple of months after the card transactions to make it harder for investigators to pin down the vulnerability.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] After the fraud was discovered it was found that tampered-with terminals could be identified as the additional circuitry increased their weight by about 100 grams.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Tens of millions of pounds are believed to have been stolen.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This vulnerability spurred efforts to implement better control of POS devices over their entire lifecycle, a practice endorsed by electronic payment security standards like those being developed by the Secure POS Vendor Alliance (SPVA).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In a February 2008 BBC *Newsnight* programme Cambridge University researchers Steven Murdoch and Saar Drimer demonstrated one example attack, to illustrate that Chip and PIN is not secure enough to justify passing the liability to prove fraud from banks onto customers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The Cambridge University exploit allowed the experimenters to obtain both card data to create a magnetic stripe and the PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In August 2016, NCR Corporation security researchers showed how credit card thieves can rewrite the code of a magnetic strip to make it appear like a chipless card, which allows for counterfeiting.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] On 11 February 2010 Murdoch and Drimer's team at Cambridge University announced that they had found "a flaw in chip and PIN so serious they think it shows that the whole system needs a re-write" that was "so simple that it shocked them".
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] A stolen card is connected to an electronic circuit and to a fake card which is inserted into the terminal ("man-in-the-middle attack").
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Any four digits can be typed in and accepted as a valid PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] A team from the BBC's *Newsnight* programme visited a Cambridge University cafeteria (with permission) with the system, and were able to pay using their own cards (a thief would use stolen cards) connected to the circuit, inserting a fake card and typing in "0000" as the PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The transactions were registered as normal, and were not picked up by banks' security systems.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] A member of the research team said, "Even small-scale criminal systems have better equipment than we have.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The amount of technical sophistication needed to carry out this attack is really quite low." The announcement of the vulnerability said, "The expertise that is required is not high (undergraduate level electronics).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The Cambridge team disagrees: they carried it out without the banks noticing, with off-the-shelf equipment with some non-sophisticated additions.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Less bulky versions could easily be made.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The ones producing such equipment for the attack need not put themselves at risk, but can sell it to anybody via the Internet.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] When approached for comment, several banks (Co-operative Bank, Barclays and HSBC) each said that this was an industry-wide issue, and referred the *Newsnight* team to the banking trade association for further comment.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] According to Phil Jones of the Consumers' Association, Chip and PIN has helped to bring down instances of card crime, but many cases remain unexplained.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The attack uses the fact that the choice of authentication method is unauthenticated, which allows the man in the middle.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The terminal asks for a PIN, gets it and gets the transaction confirmed by the card – which thinks it is doing a card-and-signature transaction, which could indeed succeed offline.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] It also works online, perhaps because of insufficient checks.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Originally, bank customers had to prove that they had not been negligent with their PIN before getting redress, but UK regulations in force from 1 November 2009 placed the onus on banks to prove that a customer has been negligent in any dispute, with the customer given 13 months to make a claim.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] At the CanSecWest conference in March 2011, Andrea Barisani and Daniele Bianco presented research uncovering a vulnerability in EMV that would allow arbitrary PIN harvesting despite the cardholder verification configuration of the card, even when the supported CVMs data is signed.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The PIN harvesting can be performed with a chip skimmer.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In essence, a CVM list that has been modified to downgrade the CVM to Offline PIN is still honoured by POS terminals, despite its signature being invalid.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In 2020, researchers David Basin, Ralf Sasse, and Jorge Toro from ETH Zurich reported a security issue affecting Visa contactless cards: lack of cryptographic protection of critical data sent by the card to the terminal during an EMV transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The data in question determines the cardholder verification method (such as PIN verification) to be used for the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The team demonstrated that it is possible to modify this data to trick the terminal into believing that no PIN is required because the cardholder was verified using their device (e.g. smartphone).
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The researchers developed a proof-of-concept Android app that effectively turns a physical Visa card into a mobile payment app (e.g.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] Apple Pay, Google Pay) to perform PIN-free, high-value purchases.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The attack is carried out using two NFC-enabled smartphones, one held near the physical card and the second held near the payment terminal.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] The attack might affect cards by Discover and China's UnionPay but this was not demonstrated in practice, in contrast to Visa cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] In early 2021, the same team disclosed that Mastercard cards are also vulnerable to a PIN bypass attack.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] They showed that criminals can trick a terminal into transacting with a Mastercard contactless card while believing it to be a Visa card.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p01] This *card brand mixup* has critical consequences since it can be used in combination with the PIN bypass for Visa to also bypass the PIN for Mastercard cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] EMV stands for "Europay, Mastercard, and Visa", the three companies that created the standard.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The standard is now managed by EMVCo, a consortium of financial companies.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Visa and Mastercard have also developed standards for using EMV cards in devices to support card not present transactions (CNP) over the telephone and Internet.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Mastercard has the Chip Authentication Program (CAP) for secure e-commerce.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Its implementation is known as EMV-CAP and supports a number of modes.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Visa has the Dynamic Passcode Authentication (DPA) scheme, which is their implementation of CAP using different default values.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] In many countries of the world, debit card and/or credit card payment networks have implemented liability shifts.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Normally, the card issuer is liable for fraudulent transactions.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] However, after a liability shift is implemented, if the ATM or merchant's point of sale terminal does not support EMV, the ATM owner or merchant is liable for the fraudulent transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Chip and PIN systems can cause problems for travellers from countries that do not issue Chip and PIN cards as some retailers may refuse to accept their chipless cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] While most terminals still accept a magnetic strip card, and the major credit card brands require vendors to accept them, some staff may refuse to take the card, under the belief that they are held liable for any fraud if the card cannot verify a PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Non-chip-and-PIN cards may also not work in some unattended vending machines at, for example, train stations, or self-service check-out tills at supermarkets.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Chip and PIN was trialled in Northampton, England from May 2003, and as a result was rolled out nationwide in the United Kingdom on 14 February 2006 with advertisements in the press and national television touting the "Safety in Numbers" slogan.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] During the first stages of deployment, if a fraudulent magnetic swipe card transaction was deemed to have occurred, the retailer was refunded by the issuing bank, as was the case prior to the introduction of Chip and PIN.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] On January 1, 2005, the liability for such transactions was shifted to the retailer; this acted as an incentive for retailers to upgrade their point of sale (PoS) systems, and most major high-street chains upgraded on time for the EMV deadline.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Many smaller businesses were initially reluctant to upgrade their equipment, as it required a completely new PoS system—a significant investment.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] New cards featuring both magnetic strips and chips are now issued by all major banks.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The replacement of pre-Chip and PIN cards was a major issue, as banks simply stated that consumers would receive their new cards "when their old card expires" — despite many people having had cards with expiry dates as late as 2007.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The card issuer Switch lost a major contract with HBOS to Visa, as they were not ready to issue the new cards as early as the bank wanted.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The Chip and PIN implementation was criticised as designed to reduce the liability of banks in cases of claimed card fraud by requiring the customer to prove that they had acted "with reasonable care" to protect their PIN and card, rather than on the bank having to prove that the signature matched.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Before Chip and PIN, if a customer's signature was forged, the banks were legally liable and had to reimburse the customer.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Until 1 November 2009 there was no such law protecting consumers from fraudulent use of their Chip and PIN transactions, only the voluntary Banking Code.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] There were many reports that banks refused to reimburse victims of fraudulent card use, claiming that their systems could not fail under the circumstances reported, despite several documented successful large-scale attacks.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The Payment Services Regulations 2009 came into force on 1 November 2009 and shifted the onus onto the banks to prove, rather than assume, that the cardholder is at fault.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] The Financial Services Authority (FSA) said "It is for the bank, building society or credit card company to show that the transaction was made by you, and there was no breakdown in procedures or technical difficulty" before refusing liability.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] After widespread identity theft due to weak security in the point-of-sale terminals at Target, Home Depot, and other major retailers, Visa, Mastercard and Discover in March 2012 – and American Express in June 2012 – announced their EMV migration plans for the United States.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Since the announcement, multiple banks and card issuers have announced cards with EMV chip-and-signature technology, including American Express, Bank of America, Citibank, Wells Fargo, JPMorgan Chase, U.S.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] In 2010, a number of companies began issuing pre-paid debit cards that incorporate Chip and PIN and allow Americans to load cash as euros or pound sterling.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] United Nations Federal Credit Union was the first United States issuer to offer Chip and PIN credit cards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] In May 2010, a press release from Gemalto (a global EMV card producer) indicated that United Nations Federal Credit Union in New York would become the first EMV card issuer in the United States, offering an EMV Visa credit card to its customers.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] JPMorgan was the first major bank to introduce a card with EMV technology, namely its Palladium card, in mid-2012.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] As of April 2016, 70% of U.S. consumers had EMV cards and as of December 2016 roughly 50% of merchants were EMV compliant.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] However, deployment has been slow and inconsistent across vendors.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Even merchants with EMV hardware may not be able to process chip transactions due to software or compliance deficiencies.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Bloomberg has also cited issues with software deployment, including changes to audio prompts for Verifone machines which can take several months to release and deploy software out.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Industry experts, however, expect more standardization in the United States for software deployment and standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] Visa and Mastercard have both implemented standards to speed up chip transactions with a goal of reducing the time for these to be under three seconds.
[src:payment-card-processing/emv-p02] These systems are labelled as Visa Quick Chip and Mastercard M/Chip Fast.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The **Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard** (**PCI DSS**) is a global data security standard that regulates how entities store, process, and transmit cardholder data (CHD) and/or sensitive authentication data (SAD).
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS includes guidelines regarding components of organizations' technical and operational system that are related to such data.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Cardholder Data refers to information including Primary Account Numbers (PAN), cardholder names, expiration dates, and service codes.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Sensitive authentication data refers to information including "full track data (magnetic-stripe data or equivalent on a chip)," card verification codes, and PINs/PIN blocks.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] This standard is administered by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, and its use is enforced by the major payment card brands.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS was created to improve and streamline the security controls organizations use when handling cardholder data and reduce credit card fraud.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These organizations, including merchants and service providers, must prove compliance to the PCI DSS through an assessment and validation process.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands issue fines and other penalties when merchants or service providers fail to prove compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Before the PCI DSS was launched, payment card information security was handled by the five major payment card brands: Visa, Mastercard, American Express, Discover, and JCB.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The intentions of each were roughly similar: to create an additional level of protection for card issuers by ensuring that merchants meet minimum levels of security when they handle payment cards and related account information.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As payment card fraud rose in the late 1990s and early 2000s, the major payment card brands felt a growing need to streamline and unify these information security standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each program had its own methods and guidance regarding compliance validation, assessments, and requirements.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To address interoperability problems among the existing standards, the combined effort by these payment card brands resulted in the release of version 1.0 of PCI DSS in December 2004.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The main payment card brands then founded the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council (PCI SSC) and aligned their policies to create the PCI DSS.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS has since been implemented and followed by numerous organizations around the world.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] MasterCard, American Express, Visa, JCB International and Discover Financial Services established the PCI SSC in September 2006 as a global administrative and governing entity that mandates the evolution and development of the PCI DSS.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Independent private organizations can also participate in PCI development as part of the PCI Security Standards Council Participating Organization Program.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To join that program, organizations must register as a PCI SSC Participating Organization (PO).
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each participating organization joins a SIG (Special Interest Group) and contributes to activities mandated by the group.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS is a living document that is regularly updated by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI SSC releases major version updates, such as version 4.0, approximately every few years.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Minor updates, such as version 4.0.1, are released more frequently and typically add small changes or clarifications.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] When updates are released, organizations have a transition period during which they must become familiar with the new changes and begin ensuring compliance with the current version.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] During the transition period, organizations are only required to be compliant with either the current version or the previous version.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each PCI DSS version has divided these six requirement groups differently, but the twelve requirements have not changed since the inception of the standard.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Testing: The processes and methodologies carried out by the assessor for the confirmation of proper implementation.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Guidance: Explains the purpose of the requirement and the corresponding content, which can assist in its proper definition.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Apply secure configurations to all system components.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect cardholder data with strong cryptography during transmission over open, public networks.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect all systems and networks from malicious software.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Develop and maintain secure systems and software.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict access to system components and cardholder data by business need to know.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Identify users and authenticate access to system components.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict physical access to cardholder data.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Log and monitor all access to system components and cardholder data.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Test security of systems and networks regularly.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Support information security with organizational policies and programs.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants that store, process, and transmit cardholder data are subject to PCI DSS standards, and thus, must be deemed PCI-compliant.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS framework classifies these entities into merchant levels that determine the type of reporting a business must complete to achieve compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A business' merchant level is determined by its dataset size which refers to the number of transactions a business makes annually.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An acquirer or payment brand may manually place an organization into a reporting level at its discretion.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Not all payment card brands use all four merchant levels, and each level's transaction volume can vary among payment card brands.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] For instance, Visa only has three merchant levels.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each card issuer maintains a table of compliance levels and a table for service providers.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to the PCI DSS, third-party service providers that store, process, or transmit cardholder data, or have access to customers’ account data are subject to PCI DSS standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers can include payment software vendors, software as a service (SaaS), data centers, and other such entities.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are required to prove PCI DSS compliance through the assessment process.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The type of reporting process a service provider must complete are dependent on the type of service provider.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are classified into levels which determine the reporting required for compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands regularly require both merchants and service providers to demonstrate PCI DSS compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS compliance involves implementing security controls that follow all requirements of the PCI DSS and passing the PCI DSS assessment process to achieve compliance validation.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major credit card brands enforce PCI DSS compliance by issuing fines for merchants who do not obtain compliance validation.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants and service providers sign business-to-business contracts with payment processors and payment card brands, which outline such fines and fees.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In the event of a merchant's compliance violation, payment card brands issue fines to the acquiring bank who then fines or otherwise penalizes the non-compliant merchant.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Obtaining PCI DSS compliance and navigating the assessment process can be complicated, which is why many businesses often struggle with this.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Verizon's 2018 Payment Security Report, 47.5% of organizations were not PCI DSS compliant during interim compliance validation.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The number of organizations achieving compliance had been steadily increasing through the early 2010s, but this increase may likely have dropped in recent years.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation involves the evaluation and confirmation that the security controls and procedures have been implemented according to the PCI DSS.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Validation occurs through an annual assessment, either by an external entity, or by self-assessment.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Perform the PCI DSS assessment of the environment.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the applicable report for the assessment according to PCI DSS guidance and instructions.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the Attestation of Compliance for Service Providers or Merchants, as applicable, in its entirety.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Submit the applicable PCI SSC documentation and the Attestation of Compliance, along with any other requested documentation to the requesting organization (those that manage compliance programs such as payment brands and acquirers (for merchants), or other requesters (for service providers)).
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Report on Compliance (ROC) is conducted by a PCI Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) and is intended to provide independent validation of an entity's compliance with the PCI DSS standard.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A completed ROC results in two documents: a ROC Reporting Template populated with detailed explanation of the testing completed, and an Attestation of Compliance (AOC) documenting that a ROC has been completed and the overall conclusion of the ROC.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ) is a validation tool intended for small to medium sized merchants and service providers to assess their own PCI DSS compliance status.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] There are multiple types of SAQ, each with a different length depending on the entity type and payment model used.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each SAQ question has a yes-or-no answer, and any "no" response requires the entity to indicate its future implementation.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As with ROCs, an attestation of compliance (AOC) based on the SAQ is also completed.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI Security Standards Council maintains a program to certify companies and individuals to perform assessment activities.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) is an individual certified by the PCI Security Standards Council to validate another entity's PCI DSS compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] QSAs must be employed and sponsored by a QSA Company, which also must be certified by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An Internal Security Assessor (ISA) is an individual who has earned a certificate from the PCI Security Standards Council for their sponsoring organization, and can conduct PCI self-assessments for their organization.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The ISA program was designed to help Level 2 merchants meet Mastercard compliance validation requirements.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISA certification empowers an individual to conduct an appraisal of his or her association and propose security solutions and controls for PCI DSS compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISAs are in charge of cooperation and participation with QSAs.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Although the PCI DSS must be implemented by all entities which process, store or transmit cardholder data and/or sensitive authentication data or could impact the security of such information, formal validation of PCI DSS compliance is not mandatory for all entities.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Visa and Mastercard require merchants and service providers to be validated according to the PCI DSS; Visa also offers a Technology Innovation Program (TIP), an alternative program which allows qualified merchants to discontinue the annual PCI DSS validation assessment.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants are eligible if they take alternative precautions against fraud, such as the use of EMV or point-to-point encryption.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Issuing banks are not required to undergo PCI DSS validation, although they must secure sensitive data in a PCI DSS-compliant manner.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Acquiring banks must comply with PCI DSS and have their compliance validated with an audit.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In a security breach, any compromised entity which was not PCI DSS-compliant at the time of the breach may be subject to additional penalties (such as fines) from card brands or acquiring banks.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] No governing body/agency requires or enforces PCI DSS compliance, but if any PCI DSS requirements conflict with country, state, or local law, the law will apply.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The European Union’s (EU) General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a legislative standard governing personal data.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] GDPR has similar security control standards as PCI DSS in regards to cardholder data because cardholder data is considered a form of personal data under GDPR.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Hence, for many European organizations, a PCI DSS breach often constitutes a GDPR breach as well, which can result in fines from both major payment card brands and the European Union.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These GDPR fines can be up to "€20 million or 4% of annual global turnover" (whichever is greatest).
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] While compliance with PCI DSS is not required by federal law in the United States, the laws of some US states refer to PCI DSS directly or make equivalent provisions.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2007, Minnesota enacted a law prohibiting the retention of some types of payment-card data more than 48 hours after authorization of a transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Nevada incorporated the standard into state law two years later, requiring compliance by merchants doing business in that state with the current PCI DSS and shielding compliant entities from liability.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The Nevada law also allows merchants to avoid liability by other approved security standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2010, Washington also incorporated the standard into state law.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Unlike Nevada's law, entities are not required to be PCI DSS-compliant; however, compliant entities are shielded from liability in the event of a data breach.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Legal scholars Edward Morse and Vasant Raval have said that by enshrining PCI DSS compliance in legislation, card networks reallocated the cost of fraud from card issuers to merchants.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major payment card brands impose fines for non-compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Some business owners, small business owners especially, criticize the PCI DSS system because the payment card brands impose fines on businesses even if no fraud occurs.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Stephen and Theodora "Cissy" McComb, owners of a small restaurant called Cisero's Ristorante and Nightclub in Park City, Utah, were fined for a breach for which two forensics firms could not find evidence.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] They claim the PCI DSS system exists primarily for major card brands to extract profit from these merchant companies rather than ensure cardholder data security.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Proponents of the PCI DSS maintain that the PCI DSS may compel businesses to pay more attention to IT security, even if minimum standards are not enough to eradicate security problems.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Former Visa chief enterprise risk officer Ellen Richey said in 2018, "No compromised entity has yet been found to be in compliance with PCI DSS at the time of a breach".
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] However, a 2008 breach of Heartland Payment Systems (validated as PCI DSS-compliant) resulted in the compromising of more than one hundred million card numbers.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Around that time, Hannaford Brothers and TJX Companies (also validated as PCI DSS-compliant) were similarly breached as a result of the allegedly-coordinated efforts of Albert Gonzalez and two unnamed Russian hackers.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In December 2013, more than forty million Target customer accounts were compromised in a data breach.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Target’s Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer at the time John Mulligan confirmed that Target was certified PCI compliant months before the breach in September 2013.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] News of incidents was widespread and called into question the adequacy of the PCI DSS.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Assessments examine the compliance of merchants and service providers with the PCI DSS at a specific point in time, frequently using sampling to allow compliance to be demonstrated with representative systems and processes.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] It is the responsibility of the merchant and service provider to achieve, demonstrate, and maintain compliance throughout the annual validation-and-assessment cycle across all systems and processes.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A breakdown in merchant and service-provider compliance with the written standard may have been responsible for the breaches; Hannaford Brothers received its PCI DSS compliance validation one day after it had been made aware of a two-month-long compromise of its internal systems.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation is required only for level 1 to 3 merchants and may be optional for Level 4, depending on the card brand and acquirer.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Visa's compliance validation details for merchants, level-4 merchant compliance-validation requirements ("Merchants processing less than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions annually and all other merchants processing up to 1 million Visa transactions annually") are set by the acquirer.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Over 80 percent of payment-card compromises between 2005 and 2007 affected level-4 merchants, who handled 32 percent of all such transactions.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] A **payment processor** is a system that enables financial transactions, commonly employed by a merchant, to handle transactions with customers from various channels such as credit cards and debit cards or bank accounts.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] They are usually broken down into two types: front-end and back-end.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Front-end processors have connections to various card associations and supply authorization and settlement services to the merchant banks' merchants.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Back-end processors accept settlements from front-end processors and, via the Federal Reserve Bank for example, move the money from the issuing bank to the merchant bank.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] In an operation that will usually take a few seconds, the payment processor will both check the details received by forwarding them to the respective card's issuing bank or card association for verification, and also carry out a series of anti-fraud measures against the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Additional parameters, including the card's country of issue and its previous payment history, are also used to gauge the probability of the transaction being approved.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Once the payment processor has received confirmation that the credit card details have been verified, the information is relayed back via the payment gateway to the merchant, who will then complete the payment transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] If verification is denied by the card association, the payment processor will relay the information to the merchant, who will then decline the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] After centuries of using metal coins, paper currency made its first appearance in China during the Tang dynasty (around the 10th century AD) and was later introduced to the West in the 17th century.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Also in the 17th century, people began to use checks as a payment method, which grew in popularity from the 1800s to the early 1900s.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] To help streamline and centralize the multiple types of currency, the U.S.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Congress passed the Federal Reserve Act in 1913.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The first payment card was created in 1950 by Ralph Schneider and Frank McNamara to allow members to use charge cards at their Diners’ Club, and consumers were required to pay their bill in full each month.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] In 1959, American Express created the first credit card that allowed users to carry a balance from month to month.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The ATM emerged in the 1960s and 1970s as part of the growing movement toward “self-service” technology.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] ATMs provided the first technology-enabled banking option that allowed consumers to conveniently deposit and withdraw cash, without being restricted to a particular bank location or business hours.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] In 1972, the first Automated Clearinghouse (ACH) association was formed in California in response to bank industry concerns that widespread check usage would outpace the technology needed to process them.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] ACH became the primary method of electronic funds transfer (EFT) for agencies, businesses, and individuals to pay or collect money online, and is still commonly used today.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Over the following decades, the evolution of payment technology accelerated.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The first digital currency is attributed to an algorithm developed by David Chaum in 1983.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The first online payment processing company was founded in 1998, first under the name Confinity, which was later changed to X.com, changing again to its current name, PayPal, in 2001.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The market continued to expand over the following two decades, branching out into a full payment processing ecosystem that includes card companies, digital wallets and apps, cryptocurrencies, payments software platforms and gateways, eCommerce partnerships, and peer-to-peer payments.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Other technologies that are vital to the payment ecosystem are data security systems and processes, automated functionality, and customer engagement tools.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Due to the many regulatory requirements levied on businesses, the modern payment processor is usually partnered with merchants through a concept known as software-as-a-service (SaaS).
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] These cloud-based features occur regardless of origination through the payment processor's integrated receivables management platform.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] This results in cost reductions, accelerated time-to-market, and improved transaction processing quality.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Electronic payments are highly susceptible to fraud and abuse.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Liability for misuse of credit card data can expose the merchant to significant financial loss if they were to attempt to manage such risks on their own.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] One way to lower this cost and liability exposure is to segment the transaction of the sale from the payment of the amount due.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Many merchants offer subscription services, which require payment from a customer every month.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] SaaS payment processors relieve the responsibility of the management of recurring payments from the merchant and maintain safe and secure the payment information, passing back to the merchant a payment "token" or unique placeholder for the card data.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Through Tokenization, merchants are able to use this token to process charges, perform refunds, or void transactions without ever storing the payment card data, which can help to make the merchant system PCI-compliant.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Tokenization can be either local (on the merchant's system) or remote (on the service provider's system); the latter provides a higher level of security against a breach.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Another method of protecting payment card data is Point to Point Encryption, which encrypts cardholder data so that clear text payment information is not accessible within the merchant's system in the event of a data breach.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Some payment processors also specialize in high-risk processing for industries that are subject to frequent chargebacks, such as adult video distribution.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The typical network architecture for modern online payment systems is a chain of service providers, each providing unique value to the payment transaction, and each adding cost to the transaction: merchant, point-of-sale (PoS) software as a service (SaaS), aggregator, credit card network, and bank.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The merchant can be a brick-and-mortar outlet or an online outlet.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The PoS SaaS provider is usually a smaller company that provides customer support to the merchant and is the receiver of the merchant's transactions.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The PoS provider represents the aggregator to merchants.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] The PoS provider transaction volumes are small compared to the aggregator transaction volumes, so a direct connection to the major credit card networks is not warranted, because of the low traffic.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] Additionally, the merchant does not handle enough traffic to warrant a direct connection to the aggregator.
[src:payment-card-processing/payment-processor] In this way, scope and responsibilities are divided among the various business partners to easily manage the technical issues that arise.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system must be secured and validated using security best practices applicable to sensitive data protection, secure storage, audit, authentication and authorization.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system provides data processing applications with the authority and interfaces to request tokens, or detokenize back to sensitive data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The security and risk reduction benefits of tokenization require that the tokenization system is logically isolated and segmented from data processing systems and applications that previously processed or stored sensitive data replaced by tokens.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Only the tokenization system can tokenize data to create tokens, or detokenize back to redeem sensitive data under strict security controls.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The token generation method must be proven to have the property that there is no feasible means through direct attack, cryptanalysis, side channel analysis, token mapping table exposure or brute force techniques to reverse tokens back to live data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Replacing live data with tokens in systems is intended to minimize exposure of sensitive data to those applications, stores, people and processes, reducing risk of compromise or accidental exposure and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Applications can operate using tokens instead of live data, with the exception of a small number of trusted applications explicitly permitted to detokenize when strictly necessary for an approved business purpose.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems may be operated in-house within a secure isolated segment of the data center, or as a service from a secure service provider.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization may be used to safeguard sensitive data involving, for example, bank accounts, financial statements, medical records, criminal records, driver's licenses, loan applications, stock trades, voter registrations, and other types of personally identifiable information (PII).
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is often used in credit card processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council defines tokenization as "a process by which the primary account number (PAN) is replaced with a surrogate value called a token.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] A PAN may be linked to a reference number through the tokenization process.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In this case, the merchant simply has to retain the token and a reliable third party controls the relationship and holds the PAN.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The token may be created independently of the PAN, or the PAN can be used as part of the data input to the tokenization technique.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The communication between the merchant and the third-party supplier must be secure to prevent an attacker from intercepting to gain the PAN and the token.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] De-tokenization is the reverse process of redeeming a token for its associated PAN value.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The security of an individual token relies predominantly on the infeasibility of determining the original PAN knowing only the surrogate value".
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The choice of tokenization as an alternative to other techniques such as encryption will depend on varying regulatory requirements, interpretation, and acceptance by respective auditing or assessment entities.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This is in addition to any technical, architectural or operational constraint that tokenization imposes in practical use.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The concept of tokenization, as adopted by the industry today, has existed since the first currency systems emerged centuries ago as a means to reduce risk in handling high value financial instruments by replacing them with surrogate equivalents.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In the physical world, coin tokens have a long history of use replacing the financial instrument of minted coins and banknotes.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In more recent history, subway tokens and casino chips found adoption for their respective systems to replace physical currency and cash handling risks such as theft.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Exonumia and scrip are terms synonymous with such tokens.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In the digital world, similar substitution techniques have been used since the 1970s as a means to isolate real data elements from exposure to other data systems.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In databases for example, surrogate key values have been used since 1976 to isolate data associated with the internal mechanisms of databases and their external equivalents for a variety of uses in data processing.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] More recently, these concepts have been extended to consider this isolation tactic to provide a security mechanism for the purposes of data protection.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In the payment card industry, tokenization is one means of protecting sensitive cardholder data in order to comply with industry standards and government regulations.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization was applied to payment card data by Shift4 Corporation and released to the public during an industry Security Summit in Las Vegas, Nevada in 2005.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The technology is meant to prevent the theft of the credit card information in storage.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Shift4 defines tokenization as: "The concept of using a non-decryptable piece of data to represent, by reference, sensitive or secret data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] To protect data over its full lifecycle, tokenization is often combined with end-to-end encryption to secure data in transit to the tokenization system or service, with a token replacing the original data on return.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] For example, to avoid the risks of malware stealing data from low-trust systems such as point of sale (POS) systems, as in the Target breach of 2013, cardholder data encryption must take place prior to card data entering the POS and not after.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also specified end-to-end encryption (certified point-to-point encryption—P2PE) for various service implementations in various PCI Council Point-to-point Encryption documents.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems share several components according to established standards.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Token mapping – this is the process of assigning the created token value to its original value.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] To enable permitted look-ups of the original value using the token as the index, a secure cross-reference database must be constructed.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Token data store – this is a central repository for the token mapping process that holds the original sensitive values and their related token values.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Sensitive data and token values must be securely kept in an encrypted format.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Strong key management procedures are required for sensitive data encryption on token data stores.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization and "classic" encryption effectively protect data if implemented properly, and a computer security system may use both.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] While similar in certain regards, tokenization and classic encryption differ in a few key aspects.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Both are cryptographic data security methods and they essentially have the same function, however they do so with differing processes and have different effects on the data they are protecting.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes without altering the type or length of data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This is an important distinction from encryption because changes in data length and type can render information unreadable in intermediate systems such as databases.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenized data can still be processed by legacy systems which makes tokenization more flexible than classic encryption.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In many situations, the encryption process is a constant consumer of processing power, hence such a system needs significant expenditures in specialized hardware and software.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Another difference is that tokens require significantly less computational resources to process.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] With tokenization, specific data is kept fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This allows tokenized data to be processed more quickly and reduces the strain on system resources.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This can be a key advantage in systems that rely on high performance.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In comparison to encryption, tokenization technologies reduce time, expense, and administrative effort while enabling teamwork and communication.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] There are many ways that tokens can be classified.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] However, there is currently no unified classification.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be single or multi-use, cryptographic or non-cryptographic, reversible or irreversible, authenticable or non-authenticable, and various combinations thereof.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In the context of payments, the difference between high and low value tokens plays a significant role.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] High-value tokens (HVT) serve as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions and are used as an instrument for completing a payment transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In order to function, they must look like actual PANs.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Multiple HVT can map back to a single PAN and a single physical credit card without the owner being aware of it.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Additionally, HVT can be limited to certain networks and/or merchants whereas PANs cannot.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] HVT can also be bound to specific devices so that anomalies between token use, physical devices, and geographic locations can be flagged as potentially fraudulent.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] HVT blocking enhances efficiency by reducing computational costs while maintaining accuracy and reducing record linkage as it reduces the number of records that are compared.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Low-value tokens (LVT) also act as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions, however they serve a different purpose.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] LVT cannot be used by themselves to complete a payment transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In order for an LVT to function, it must be possible to match it back to the actual PAN it represents, albeit only in a tightly controlled fashion.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Using tokens to protect PANs becomes ineffectual if a tokenization system is breached, therefore securing the tokenization system itself is extremely important.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] First generation tokenization systems use a database to map from live data to surrogate substitute tokens and back.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This requires the storage, management, and continuous backup for every new transaction added to the token database to avoid data loss.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Another problem is ensuring consistency across data centers, requiring continuous synchronization of token databases.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Significant consistency, availability and performance trade-offs, per the CAP theorem, are unavoidable with this approach.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This overhead adds complexity to real-time transaction processing to avoid data loss and to assure data integrity across data centers, and also limits scale.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Storing all sensitive data in one service creates an attractive target for attack and compromise, and introduces privacy and legal risk in the aggregation of data Internet privacy, particularly in the EU.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Another limitation of tokenization technologies is measuring the level of security for a given solution through independent validation.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] With the lack of standards, the latter is critical to establish the strength of tokenization offered when tokens are used for regulatory compliance.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The method of generating tokens may also have limitations from a security perspective.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] With concerns about security and attacks to random number generators, which are a common choice for the generation of tokens and token mapping tables, scrutiny must be applied to ensure proven and validated methods are used versus arbitrary design.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Random-number generators have limitations in terms of speed, entropy, seeding and bias, and security properties must be carefully analysed and measured to avoid predictability and compromise.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Stateless tokenization allows live data elements to be mapped to surrogate values randomly, without relying on a database, while maintaining the isolation properties of tokenization.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] November 2014, American Express released its token service which meets the EMV tokenization standard.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Other notable examples of tokenization-based payment systems, according to the EMVCo standard, include Google Wallet, Apple Pay, Samsung Pay, Microsoft Wallet, Fitbit Pay and Garmin Pay.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Visa uses tokenization techniques to provide a secure online and mobile shopping.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Using blockchain, as opposed to relying on trusted third parties, it is possible to run highly accessible, tamper-resistant databases for transactions.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] With help of blockchain, tokenization is the process of converting the value of a tangible or intangible asset into a token that can be exchanged on the network.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This enables the tokenization of conventional financial assets, for instance, by transforming rights into a digital token backed by the asset itself using blockchain technology.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Besides that, tokenization enables the simple and efficient compartmentalization and management of data across multiple users.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Individual tokens created through tokenization can be used to split ownership and partially resell an asset.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Consequently, only entities with the appropriate token can access the data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Numerous blockchain companies support asset tokenization.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In 2019, eToro acquired Firmo and renamed as eToroX.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Through its Token Management Suite, which is backed by USD-pegged stablecoins, eToroX enables asset tokenization.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization of equity is facilitated by STOKR, a platform that links investors with small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokens issued through the STOKR platform are legally recognized as transferable securities under European Union capital market regulations.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Breakers enable tokenization of intellectual property, allowing content creators to issue their own digital tokens.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be distributed to a variety of project participants.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Without intermediaries or governing body, content creators can integrate reward-sharing features into the token.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Building an alternate payments system requires a number of entities working together in order to deliver near field communication (NFC) or other technology based payment services to the end users.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] One of the issues is the interoperability between the players and to resolve this issue the role of trusted service manager (TSM) is proposed to establish a technical link between mobile network operators (MNO) and providers of services, so that these entities can work together.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can play a role in mediating such services.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization as a security strategy lies in the ability to replace a real card number with a surrogate (target removal) and the subsequent limitations placed on the surrogate card number (risk reduction).
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] If the surrogate value can be used in an unlimited fashion or even in a broadly applicable manner, the token value gains as much value as the real credit card number.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In these cases, the token may be secured by a second dynamic token that is unique for each transaction and also associated to a specific payment card.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Example of dynamic, transaction-specific tokens include cryptograms used in the EMV (Europay, Mastercard, and Visa) specification.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, an industry-wide set of guidelines that must be met by any organization that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data, mandates that credit card data must be protected when stored.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization, as applied to payment card data, is often implemented to meet this mandate, replacing credit card and automated clearing house (ACH) numbers in some systems with a random value or string of characters.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be formatted in a variety of ways.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Some token service providers or tokenization products generate the surrogate values in such a way as to match the format of the original sensitive data.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In the case of payment card data, a token might be the same length as a primary account number (bank card number) and contain elements of the original data such as the last four digits of the card number.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] When a payment card authorization request is made to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, a token might be returned to the merchant instead of the card number, along with the authorization code for the transaction.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The token is stored in the receiving system while the actual cardholder data is mapped to the token in a secure tokenization system.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Storage of tokens and payment card data must comply with current PCI standards, including the use of strong cryptography.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is currently in standards definition in ANSI X9 as X9.119 Part 2.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] X9 is responsible for the industry standards for financial cryptography and data protection including payment card PIN management, credit and debit card encryption and related technologies and processes.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also stated support for tokenization in reducing risk in data breaches, when combined with other technologies such as Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) and assessments of compliance to PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Visa Inc. released Visa Tokenization Best Practices for tokenization uses in credit and debit card handling applications and services.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] In March 2014, EMVCo LLC released its first payment tokenization specification for EMV.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] PCI DSS is the most frequently utilized standard for Tokenization systems used by payment industry players.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can render it more difficult for attackers to gain access to sensitive data outside of the tokenization system or service.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Implementation of tokenization may simplify the requirements of the PCI DSS, as systems that no longer store or process sensitive data may have a reduction of applicable controls required by the PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] This validation is particularly important in tokenization, as the tokens are shared externally in general use and thus exposed in high risk, low trust environments.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] The infeasibility of reversing a token or set of tokens to a live sensitive data must be established using industry accepted measurements and proofs by appropriate experts independent of the service or solution provider.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Not all organizational data can be tokenized, and needs to be examined and filtered.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] When databases are utilized on a large scale, they expand exponentially, causing the search process to take longer, restricting system performance, and increasing backup processes.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] A database that links sensitive information to tokens is called a vault.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] With the addition of new data, the vault's maintenance workload increases significantly.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] For ensuring database consistency, token databases need to be continuously synchronized.
[src:payment-card-processing/tokenization-data-security] Apart from that, secure communication channels must be built between sensitive data and the vault so that data is not compromised on the way to or from storage.
